## Overview

This demonstrates the use of "Honor System Protected Web Content" (HPWC).

Any content designtated HPWC is content that the customer cannot see, unless they first log-in to the site.

After loogging in, the customer can easily view, copy, paste, and save the HPWC to their local machine if they choose.

Moreover, after logging in, the customer can share the URL to the HPWC if they choose. For cases where such sharing is not deemed appropriate, it is usually sufficient to indicate that as part of the message that specifies the need to first log-in.

Because of the nature of HPWC content, it is not recommended for any high-risk information that would constitute a violation of any relevant Acceptable Use Policies, were it saved to a local machine or workstation.

## Example 001 -- Hertz Rental Car Codes

* The Business Office provides proprietary codes that allow for special discounts.
* These proprietary codes are not intended for use by anyone outside the UO Campus Community.
* In order to remind people of the intended use of these codes, and to prevent accidental disclosure or sharing, these are designated as HPWC.

### Linking to the HPWC

To link to the relevant HPWC, it is sufficient to use an HTML anchor-tag reference (hashtag style) that points to the section of the page with the protected content.

* https://ba.uoregon.edu/content/vehicle-rental#hertz-car-rental-contract

### Viewing the HPWC as a non-logged-in user

When a non-authenticated user tries to view the content, they simply see a box that indicates the authentication requirement.

* <img src="data:image/png;base64," />

### Viewing the HPWC as a logged-in user

When an authenticated user tries to view the content, they see the content that is contained within the page fragment.

* <img src="data:image/png;base64," />

### Viewing the HPWC as a logged-in user with rights to modify the content

When an authenticated user with sufficient permissions tries to view the content, they see the content that is contained within the page fragment.

They also see links that allow them to manage and edit the content.

* <img src="data:image/png;base64," />
